Git:
Git is a version control system (VCS) used to track changes in the code.
It runs locally on computer.

Github:
It is a cloud platfoam where repositries are stored.

3 terms:
Repository: A Git-tracked project folder that stores your files and their version history. 
Working Directory: The folder where you create and modify project files.
Staging Area (Index): A temporary (buffer) area before committing files.

Origin: It is alias for the github repo.
Heaad: HEAD in Git is a reference to the latest commit on the currently checked-out branch.

Commands:

1. git push: It is used to share local repository changes to a remote repository.
   Eg: git push origin main

2. git pull: Downloads the latest changes from the remote repository and 
               merges them into your current branch.
               Eg: git pull origin main

3. git fetch: Downloads the latest changes from the remote repository 
               without merging them into your current branch.

4. git fork: Creates a copy on GitHub. Done using github

5. git clone: Creates a copy on the local computer
6. git log: shows commit history of current branch
7. git reflog: shows the history of where HEAD and branch pointers have moved.

Used to create branch: "git branch feature"
For switch between branches: "git switch feature" / git checkout feature
For merging feature branch into main branch: come to main branch then write "git merge feature"
Used to delete branch "git branch -D <branch-name>" even it is not merged for merged use -d.

Types of merging:
1. Fast-Forward Merge: A merge where Git simply moves the target branch pointer forward because it has no new commits.
2. Three-Way Merge: A merge where Git combines changes from two diverged branches by creating a new merge commit.

git push -u origin main:
-u (--set-upstream): Sets the remote tracking branch for the current local branch,
allowing future git push and git pull commands without specifying the remote and branch name.


